# Blair Brand Profile — Example

> This is an example of a completed brand profile.
> Your real brand.md is generated by running `/blair:start` in Claude Code.
> brand.md is gitignored — it stays private to your project.

> **New in v3.0:** The Pipeline section tracks your CRM data so Blair can connect marketing outputs to revenue outcomes. Fill it in during `/blair:start --deep` or add it manually with `/blair:update pipeline`.

---

## Product
- Name: Dispatch
- One-liner: Project management software for independent designers — proposals, client communication, and invoicing in one place.
- Category: Client management for freelancers
- Stage: growing

## Audience
- Primary ICP: Freelance graphic and UX designers, 1-3 person studios, billing $3k-$15k/month in client retainers, currently juggling Notion + email + invoicing separately
- Secondary segments: Freelance copywriters and brand strategists with similar workflow pain
- Not for: Agencies with 10+ staff, enterprise teams, developers building software products

## Positioning
- Category: Client management for freelancers
- Key differentiator: Only tool that combines proposals, project tracking, client feedback, and invoicing — no integrations required
- Proof points:
  1. Average time-to-payment dropped from 22 days to 4 days after switching
  2. 2,400 freelancers across 40 countries
  3. NPS of 71 — highest in category per G2 reviews

## Voice & Tone
- Personality: direct, warm, no-fluff
- Hard bans: "streamline", "solution", "synergy", "game-changer", corporate passive voice
- Reference brand: Basecamp — honest, opinionated, anti-enterprise

## Competitors
- HoneyBook: More features, more complexity, built for photographers and event planners — not designers
- Dubsado: Powerful but steep learning curve, feels like a CRM not a project tool
- Notion: Flexible but requires building everything from scratch, no invoicing

## Goals
- Current priority: acquisition
- Active channels: LinkedIn, email list (4,200 subscribers), word of mouth
- Constraints: No paid budget yet, two-person team, no time for long-form content

## Assets
- Existing content: 12 blog posts at dispatch.so/blog, 3 case studies
- Brand colors: #1A1A2E (navy), #E94560 (coral), #F5F5F5 (off-white)
- Fonts: Inter (UI), Freight Display (headings)

## Research sources (optional)
- Trusted URLs: `https://g2.com/products/dispatch`, `https://honeybook.com/pricing`
- Internal files: none
- Notes: Treat G2 cons as directional; confirm big claims on sales calls

## Pipeline (marketing-attribution log — not a CRM replacement)
- CRM: HubSpot (free tier)
- Pipeline stages: Lead → MQL → Demo Scheduled → Proposal → Closed Won / Lost
- Current monthly lead volume: ~40 leads/month
- Lead → demo rate: 22%
- Demo → close rate: 18%
- Average deal size: $1,200/year
- Current CAC: ~$85 (fully loaded)
- Marketing attribution: tracked manually in HubSpot
